I had only ordered Boston Market online once, before the other day. I attempted to order from Uber Eats, but there were no driver nearby because of the bad weather.  When I put my order in, I was under the impression that Boston Market had their own delivery drivers. I ordered at 6pm, and after a while I called because the order was taking longer than normal. So I gave the location a call, and at this point I met the most sweet, professional, down to earth employee over the phone! J (Jay) was extremely knowledgeable in her position, and of the Bostom Market community in general. She explained they partner with a 3rd party delivery service, and they were waiting for the driver. She took it a step further and explained the rewards program and delivery process to me. She even broke down of when my order was put together, picked up (she called the 3rd party on my behalf to try getting a driver sooner) and how long it should take to get to me. She told me to call back 30 min after we got off the phone (the time almost being 8)if my order never arrived, and she would start a refund process for me. but thankfully it arrived, and It was perfect! What I appreciated most was not only did she offer to fix my issue, but she empathized with me. Also, each time she answered the phone it was a perfect greeting, and excitement to give me an update on my order. I dont know her position, but I hope she's bumped to manager or gets a raise because she was everything you could ask for in customer service! I will definitely be ordering from this location always!

This is the Boston Market on N Ashland. Poor experience, despite the decent quality of the food... and I've loved this brand in the past.  Confusing, disjointed  menu posted along 2 walls (always a bad practice, and this one is a long way from the food itself). The order-taker got my order wrong, giving me, and charging me, for 1 corn bread + another order of it; he was unable, or unwilling, to speak above a whisper and make himself understood throughout the order process. As for the pricing, they have all the sides displayed together, but some, like the creamed spinach, are priced differently than the others,  leaving the customer feeling cheated somehow in the transction.  This is just an example of blatant "demand-pricing" very clumsily handled, Boston Market. And it's costing you repeat business; so is it worth it?
